tegorize my own behaviour within well bounded quadrants of such subjective aspects as respect, professionalism and perseverance, I attempt to recount a recent experience, which, albeit being apparently a common workplace disposition, helps me identify the manifestation of these attributes in me.\r\nDuring a solution phase involving third party vendors, I was challenged with the aspects of development efforts and the evaluated hardware augmentation proposed. The customer refuted both metrics as being inappropriate against a CAPEX limitation.\r\nI attempted to alleviate the concern by drawing upon the process diligence and promised to come up with an objective response to the reported inappropriateness of the proposal. Faced with the dual challenge of questioning the trust and professionalism of major stakeholders in the process, viz., the development and the infrastructure experts respectively, I approached them with the request to understand whether there was room for improvement in our proposal with all the professionalism that I could muster.\r\nI approached the developer with sincere respect of her experience to review the proposal critically with only the mandate that she might have considered an effort that may not be required to be expended but considered only as part of standard approaches.\r\nI also appealed to the technical architect to review if the augmentation proposed could absolutely be tied to the new requirement or was rather in line with general capacity augmentation required as part of standard operating procedures.\r\nThe results were beyond my expectations. The development expert responded with a significant reduction in effort noting that there had been inadvertent inclusion of components due to standard templates in the estimation tool. The technology expert responded by saying that the diligence had indicated that although the current proposal was correct, a related domain had corrected an erroneous CAPEX order that was inappropriately raised 