LL,422,'EJALBAN',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-15 04:09:45','Pending'),('EJMNNRJ','darsana.p@ericsson.com','Bangalore','EGANVAI','BUGS GSI OSS Adaptation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,423,'ECHAARU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-15 04:07:42','Pending'),('EVIRGAG','vineet.kumar.garg@ericsson.com','Pune','EPUNAGR','RSSA OP CSI Media & Application CAC',NULL,NULL,'One of my favorite writer says \"Everything is difficult before it is easy\". It reminds me of my very early days of IT career. I use to work on a database called Ingres which has 4GL forms to develop application screens. At that time Ingres released a new version Ingres OpenServer which had backwards compatibility challenges and needed a lot of code changes in 100s of 4GL forms written for ERP system. All seniors were scratching their heads to find efficient way to do it. Based on my initial analysis, I mentioned to them the possibility of writing a shell script to do all the required changes on a single click. Obviously no one took me seriously as I was just a fresher. I took up the challenge and relentlessly kept trying for several late nights, and finally created a UNIX script. I tested it locally and then presented to my seniors who were amazed with the results and appreciated my effort. This instance boosted myself-confidence multifold. That\'s what is called perseverance.','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',424,'EPPPRRR',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-15 05:26:16','Pending'),('EKUDREV','revathy.k.k@ericsson.com','Guindy Chennai','ESULNAY','BUGS GSI SDT DU IN DDM1','','','','Automation! The GIANT word in Ericsson world across all platforms..\r\nHighly focused goals and programs to achieve the same - just not another simple task isn\'t?!\r\nWell.. here comes my story on how Ericsson values were observed in certain giant automation programs that I was Pioneering.\r\n\r\nEricsson gifted me with the best of automation opportunity - to be part of increase in automation numbers in Field Service Organizations of RNAM and RWCE regions.\r\nBoth regions were unique in their own core org values and WOW. All thro’ the two assignments, I learnt that though automation has one meaning from system perspective, it means different for every human!\r\nSo how do you measure your success? If system does everything and reduces manual intervention are you all good?! Are our KPI\'s associated only with automation numbers?! If you say yes - I bet you got it wrong!\r\nSurprisingly…Automation is totally about people!! \r\nHow good they feel with the system doing things? \r\nHow much they believe that it eases their daily chores?\r\nHow much positive impact did it leave on their efficiency increase? \r\nIn one statement - HOW SATISFIED IS YOUR WORKFORCE?!!!\r\nRings a bell?? Yes exactly - these organizations tagged automation success to DIALOG Survey results from their field force - Dispatchers and the Field Technicians!\r\nWe might think we implemented great solution and automation numbers have roared high up! but FSO users have to \"experience\" the goodness and it must reflect in DIALOG survey. This was the goal set by the local organizations - which best explains how much Ericsson values its employees and “RESPECTS” their behavior towards system and organization changes.\r\nAligning technical project goals with DIALOG survey results was the toughest challenge for the automation team.\r\nWe have to hold on tight to our course of action, believe and make people believe that the technical changes we implemented will ease their current WOW and stick to our goal patiently....because at the end of the day we RESPECT the end users and foresee for their comfort with changes.\r\nBoth projects were executed for more than a year with lots of criticism and constant system tuning and yes - of course at the end.. People of the field service organization gave accolades to our work when they experienced efficiency in all perspectives! That was the success earned by our program!!\r\n\r\nMiracles need not happen! With Respect for people’s view, Perseverance in your actions, being able to bear difficulties calmly and with complete ownership, with Professional responsibility, commitment and hard work... success is always in my (our) hands.. Just because I am (in) Ericsson!\r\n','','','','','','',NULL,NULL,425,'EGANVIK',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-18 08:47:11','Pending'),('EMRARAJ','m.ravi.raja@ericsson.com','GURGAON','EGOEMUK','BUGS GSI EMM 1','','','',' \r\n\r\nThough at the time of entry, I was totally apprised of the core values on which Ericsson stood stead-fastedly for all these years, the 4.5 years stint I had so far with them gave me  the practical lessons. \r\n\r\nI was deputed to Cameroon on on–site visit in 2012 being entrusted with an activity o live upgrade of EMM & DDS. I landed at Douala, thoroughly amazed by its natural beauty.  I  got a go ahead from the client for the activity. As things were to turn out, the activity did not progress and the upgrade  was showing an error.  No way to steer clear.  The question ‘what could be the issue?’ was haunting me. The time-slot got over and the activity was declared as failed. Obviously, the client was disappointed. The local Ericsson there had enough reasons to raise hue and cry due to the likely implications on their future activities.  Some colleagues of mine had also their own share of doubts on my compliance. Though I too nurtured  doubts on the compliance level, I double-checked and found that to be fine at my end.  It was decided to raise a  CSR.  The PDU after investigations suggested a way forward.  I moved all  the traffic and tried the procedure on other node.  Alas, it miserably failed.  The PDU was subsequently requested for a better solution.  In the meanwhile, I realized  that the causative reason for the flop could be  “ not meeting the requirement of storage for DDS”  in view of the huge amount of  data to be generated.  Though the  client was not ready initially,   they  conceded later. I  could make the initial lead but on the final run-up,  the procedure failed. The client was deservedly annoyed. They opined that their production system was being used as a  test system  resulting in huge cost escalations.  Finally PDU raised a ticket with SUN (now Solaris) and  in a span of time they gave us a patch to be installed during upgrade. This time, despite being nervous-ridden,  I ventured upon and the activity proceeded without any hitch  and the mission achieved success. I was damn happy !!  \r\n\r\nAnother opportunity for similar activity in Digicel Martinique. Though things were going fine until  90% level; due to some issues  the downtime exhausted. The client was not receptive for one hour extension and  insisted for  rollback. Though fuming inside,  I had to comply with the client’s wishes.  The roll back  too had  unexpected hitches.   With  the back-up,  2 emergency CSRs, 48 hrs of non-stop efforts and an empty stomach,  the system was rolled back.  Me and the client heaved a sigh of relief. Subsequently when I was in another country for on-site, a colleague of mine who was entrusted with  re-doing the failed activity in Digicel Martinique was on a tele-conference with me for hours to resolve the issue as his attempts too failed.  Pooling of inputs of both of us made the activity to finally take-off.  He, me and our Mentor Ericsson succeeded. I learnt my life time practical lessons on “perseverance, respect and professionalism”.','','','','','','',NULL,NULL,426,'EGANVAI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-05-15 10:12:52','Pending'),('ESHRAMY','ramya.shankar@ericsson.com','BANGALORE','ESUNAGG','BUGS GSI OSS OSS-RC Adaptation','','','','Fresh out of Campus,I joined Ericsson as a GET.Ericsson brought people from different states,different colleges and different technical backgrounds, all together for training.Ericsson provided a diverse platform to break the ice and form a deep bond of friendship.I learnt to 